# Red Hat Demo Conventions

## Container Images

- ALWAYS use Red Hat UBI9 as the base container image (`registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9/ubi`, `ubi9/ubi-minimal`, or `ubi9/ubi-micro`)
- NEVER use community images (alpine, debian, ubuntu) when a UBI equivalent exists
- Pull images from `registry.access.redhat.com` or `registry.redhat.io`
- Use multi-stage builds with UBI9 for final runtime images
- Name container build files `Containerfile` (not `Dockerfile`) to align with Podman/Buildah conventions

## CLI Tooling

- Use `podman` instead of `docker` for container operations on RHEL
- Use `oc` CLI for OpenShift operations (not raw `kubectl` unless targeting upstream K8s)
- Use `ansible-navigator` over `ansible-playbook` for AAP-aligned execution
- Use `ansible-builder` for building Execution Environments
- Use `openstack` CLI for RHOSP operations

## OpenShift Resources

- Deploy applications via certified Operators from the Red Hat Operator catalog
- Use OpenShift Routes (not bare Ingress) for external traffic
- Use `DeploymentConfig` only for legacy; prefer `Deployment` for new demos
- Use OpenShift templates or Helm charts from the certified catalog

## Demo Project Structure

Organize demo repos with a consistent layout:

```
setup/              # Numbered shell scripts (00-prereqs.sh, 01-install.sh, ...)
  full-setup.sh     # Runs all setup scripts in order
manifests/          # OpenShift/K8s YAML organized by component
  operators/        # Operator subscriptions and instances
  monitoring/       # PrometheusRule, Alertmanager config
ansible/            # Playbooks, roles, rulebooks, EE definition
  playbooks/
  roles/
  rulebooks/
  execution-environment/
demo/               # Runnable demo scenarios
  scenarios/
    01-scenario-name/
      trigger.sh
      cleanup.sh
docs/               # Architecture, walkthrough, prerequisites
```

## Documentation References

- Always cite official Red Hat documentation at `docs.redhat.com` or `access.redhat.com`
- Reference product version explicitly (e.g., "OpenShift 4.16", "RHEL 9.4", "AAP 2.5")
- Link to Red Hat Customer Portal knowledge base for troubleshooting

## Naming and Branding

- Use official product names: "Red Hat OpenShift", "Red Hat Enterprise Linux", "Red Hat Ansible Automation Platform"
- Do not abbreviate to unofficial short forms in user-facing text
- Use "OpenShift" (not "OKD") when referring to the commercial product

## Security Defaults

- Enable SELinux enforcing mode in RHEL configurations
- Use TLS for all service-to-service communication
- Follow principle of least privilege for RBAC definitions
- Use Red Hat SSO / Keycloak for authentication demos where applicable
